Common name: Santa Maria River at Santa Maria
Notes: This large river flows right next to the town of Santa Maria and is the confluence of the Sisquoc and Cuyama River. This river is charecterized by its wide floodplane channel and gravely banks, and generally has low flow. During storms the Santa Maria can swell to large flows rapidly, which can pose hazards to swimmers and the unhoused people that live in the flooplane near the town of Santa Maria.
Local_Rec: Do not swim in this river, its gross and can expose you to agricultural and city runoff.

Notes: At this location the Sisquoc River is fed by waters form the San Rafael Mountains in the San Rafael Wildreness. This river is free flowing and undammed meaning that changed in weather have the potential to cause large flutuations in flow. As it is free flowing it supports populations of the endangered steelhead trout. For these reasons please be extra respectful to take care of the river as you swim. In the dry season it is normal for this river to not flow.
Local_Rec: Only swim in this river if you are in the in the wilderness area or in the mountains. Backpacking should give you the best access to swimming areas.

Common name: Santa Ynez River at Lompoc Airport
Creek name: SANTA YNEZ R A H ST NR LOMPOC CA
Notes: The Santa Ynez River flows throught east to west throught the Santa Ynez Valley and outputs to the ocean near the city of Lompoc. This river drains the north slope of the Santa Ynez Mountains and the south slope of the San Rafael Mountains making it watershed 890 square miles. This river can have flashy flows during the wet season and can be completely dry in the summers. This river is home threatened steelhead populations and in some locations golden beavers. At this location the stream is near the end of its course, and it is somewhat urban. The Red Rocks swimming hole is a highly recommended swimming location of the Santa Ynez River
Local_Rec: Only swim on this river if you are in the mountanous areas of the watershed. Red Rock swimming hole is a local favorite, located in the Los Padres National Forest.

Notes: Zaca Creek is a small tributary of the Santa Ynez River fed by waters from the Purisima Hills. It joins the Santa Ynez below the Santa Ynez Airport and lake Cachuma.
Local_Rec: Although you may be able to swim here, the flows are generally unimpressive and will likely not lead to a very pleasant experience.

Creek name: ALAMO PINTADO C NR SOLVANG CA
Notes: Alamo Pintado Creek is a small tributary of the Santa Ynez River and drains the hills surrounding the city of Solvang. Near Solvang the creek becomes urban and less fit for swimming.
Local_Rec: Although you may be able to swim here, the flows are generally unimpressive and will likely not lead to a very pleasant experience.

Notes: The Carpenteria Creek drains the portions of the Santa Ynez Mountains including Snowball Mountain. At this location the creek is urban but above the town of Carpeteria the creek becomes more wild and more suitable for swimming.
Local_Rec: Only swim here if you are well above the city of Carpenteria, swimming at or below carpenteria can expose you to city runoff.

Notes: Montecito Creek drains portions of the Santa Ynez Mountains. At this location the creek is urban but above the town of Carpenteria the creek becomes more wild and possibly more swimable.
Local_Rec: Only swim here if you are well above the city of Montecito, swimming at or below Montecito can expose you to city runoff.

Notes: Mission Creek drains 7,400 acres including parts of the Los Padres National Forest. This creek goes through downtown Santa Barbara. It is unadvisable to swim in the urban portions of this creek, due to channelizations and water quality concerns.
Local_Rec: Only swim here if you are well above the city of Santa Barbara, swimming at or below Santa Barbara can expose you to city runoff.

Creek name: SAN JOSE C NR GOLETA CA
Notes: San Jose Creek is an urban stream that goes through the town of goleta and discharges to the ocean at Goleta Beach. This stream drains bush peak, and is potentially accessible via San Marcos Pass road. Swimmn is not advisable in the urban portions of this creek.
Local_Rec: Only swim here if you are well above the city of Goleta, swimming at or below Goleta can expose you to city runoff. Flows are typically not high making the swimming experience not very good.

Notes: San Pedro Creek is an urban stream that goes through the town of Goleta and discharges to the ocean at Goleta Beach. Swiming is not advisable at or below the urban portions of this creek.

Notes: Maria Ygnacio Creek is an urban stream that goes through the town of Goleta and discharges to the ocean at Goleta Beach. This stream was named after the Barbareno Chumash woman name Maria Ygnacia who owned a land in the area. She was key in preserving aspects of the Barbareno Chumash language and cultural practices. Swiming is not advisable at or below the urban portions of this creek.
Local_Rec: Only swim here if you are well above the city of Goleta, swimming at or below Goleta can expose you to city runoff. Flows are typically not high making the swimming experience not very good.

Notes: At this location the Cuyama River drains the Chumash Wildreness area of the Los Padres National Forest. Downstream it joins with the Sisquoc River forming the Santa Maria River.
Local_Rec: Swim at Red Rocks swimming hole if you are already in the Los Padres National Forest area.
